&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; e.g i am testing a method:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; void dispatchEvent(Event event)
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; which inside calls handleEvent(event) , in a class called Handle
&gt; &gt; (this is also a void method)
&gt; &gt;
&gt; 
&gt; Can you construct the object defining dispatchEvent() with a mock
&gt; representation of a Handle.  The MockHandle would effectively just 
eat the
&gt; event, and define a wasHandled() method indicating whether the 
event was
&gt; received.
&gt; 
&gt;     public void testEventReceived() {
&gt; 
&gt;         MockHandle handle = new MockHandle();
&gt;         Foo f = new Foo(handle);
&gt; 
&gt;         f.dispatchEvent(event);
&gt; 
&gt;         assertTrue(handle.wasHandled());
&gt;     }
&gt; 
&gt; Notice that by using composition - Foo is composed of a Handle - 
the design
&gt; is more testable _and_ flexible.  Foo could use different 
implementations of
&gt; Handles without requiring modification.  Whenever I find something 
difficult
&gt; to test, it&#39;s an opportunity for a design improvement.
